<subSubSection id="C35DAAAEFFC10838FF3FFC4481823B2E" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF8F925FFC10838FF3FFC4481823B2E" blockId="28.[151,1437,937,1719]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FF3FFC44800D3CC5" bold="true" box="[199,328,973,999]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Etymology</emphasis>
: The name 
<taxonomicName id="4C4782A6FFC10838FE2CFC4783503CC5" authorityName="Johansson" authorityYear="2021" box="[468,533,974,999]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Nyxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FE2CFC4783503CC5" box="[468,533,974,999]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Nyxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from Nyx, who is the personification of the night in Greek mythology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35DAAAEFFC10838FF3FFB9C823E3A2A" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF8F925FFC10838FF3FFB9C823E3A2A" blockId="28.[151,1437,937,1719]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FF3FFB9C807F3B0D" bold="true" box="[199,314,1045,1071]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Defined by the unique combination of the presence of a distinct postpectal carina, almost complete occipital carina, the conspicuously bent radial vein, angular and partly sinuous discocubitus and untwisted mandible. It superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C4782A6FFC10838FE02FBD782003B55" authority="Brauns, 1889" authorityName="Brauns" authorityYear="1889" box="[506,837,1117,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Stauropoctonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FE02FBD783EC3B5A" box="[506,681,1118,1144]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Stauropoctonus</emphasis>
Brauns, 1889
</taxonomicName>
, which have strongly narrowed and twisted mandibles and more strongly bent radius at the junction with pterostigma or the tropical genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4782A6FFC10838FBCCFB0884083BB9" authority="Townes, 1971" authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1971" box="[1076,1357,1153,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Lepiscelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FBCCFB0885EF3BB9" box="[1076,1194,1153,1179]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Lepiscelus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFD684D4FFC10838FB57FB0B84083BB9" author="Townes, H. K." box="[1199,1357,1153,1180]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" pagination="1 - 372" refId="ref17772" refString="Townes, H. K. (1971) The genera of Ichneumonidae, Part 4. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, No. 17, 1 - 372." type="book chapter" year="1971">Townes, 1971</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which lacks occipital carina. Also similar to the afrotropical genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4782A6FFC10838FCBAFB2C851A3B9D" authority="Townes, 1973" authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1973" box="[834,1119,1189,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Laticoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FCBAFB2C82F23B9D" box="[834,951,1189,1215]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Laticoleus</emphasis>
Townes, 1973
</taxonomicName>
, which is a very rare genus, primarily occurring in African forests, but with the postpectal carina complete and the occipital carina interrupted in its lower part, characters which cannot be attributed to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4782A6FFC10838FD07FB6482313A25" authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1973" box="[767,884,1261,1287]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Laticoleus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FD07FB6482313A25" box="[767,884,1261,1287]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Laticoleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35DAAAEFFC10838FF3FFA9880873995" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF8F925FFC10838FF3FFA9880873995" blockId="28.[151,1437,937,1719]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FF3FFA9880143A09" bold="true" box="[199,337,1297,1323]" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Description</emphasis>
: Face narrow, inner orbits converging ventrally, in anterior view about as wide as the widest part of the compound eye (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FE8BFABC80963A6D" box="[371,467,1333,1359]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1488,1512]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-16@29.[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 19. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) scutellum and propodeum, dorsal view; C) head, anterior view; D) head, lateral view; E) fore tibia spur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226076/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig 19C</figureCitation>
). Ocelli very large. Occipital carina complete dorsally and laterally, but absent slightly before junction with hypostomal carina. Clypeus very wide and short in anterior view, distinctly convex in lateral view (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FF25FAF480003AB5" box="[221,325,1405,1431]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1488,1512]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-16@29.[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 19. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) scutellum and propodeum, dorsal view; C) head, anterior view; D) head, lateral view; E) fore tibia spur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226076/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 19D</figureCitation>
). Mandibles untwisted, its margins weakly converging towards the tip (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FB99FAF4858F3AB5" box="[1121,1226,1405,1431]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1569,1593]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-231@30.[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Mandibles anterior view; B) postpectal carina, posteroventral view; C) central part of fore wing; D) hind tarsal claws." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226078/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
). Mandibular teeth equal in length. Mandibular gape right angled with internal angles. Antennae slender, filiform. Mesopleuron with fine dense punctures that partially form weak longitudinal striae. Scutellum wide, polished with lateral carinae (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FA97FA4C818C3921" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1488,1512]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-16@29.[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 19. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) scutellum and propodeum, dorsal view; C) head, anterior view; D) head, lateral view; E) fore tibia spur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226076/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 19B</figureCitation>
). Propodeum with carination and sculpture as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4782A6FFC10838FD0BFA6082333921" authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1835" box="[755,886,1513,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Enicospilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FD0BFA6082333921" box="[755,886,1513,1539]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Enicospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with an evenly curved anterior transverse carina (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FF58F98480423905" box="[160,263,1549,1575]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1488,1512]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-16@29.[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 19. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) scutellum and propodeum, dorsal view; C) head, anterior view; D) head, lateral view; E) fore tibia spur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226076/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 19B</figureCitation>
). Sculpture posterior to carina rugulose, anterior to carina smooth. Epicnemial carina with pleurosternal angles inconspicuous, strongly obtuse. Postpectal carina well developed, complete (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FBA8F9B885FD3969" box="[1104,1208,1585,1611]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1569,1593]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-231@30.[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Mandibles anterior view; B) postpectal carina, posteroventral view; C) central part of fore wing; D) hind tarsal claws." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226078/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 20B</figureCitation>
). Wings with radius distinctly curved and widened before junction with pterostigma (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FC84F9DC82A0394D" box="[892,997,1621,1647]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1569,1593]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-231@30.[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Mandibles anterior view; B) postpectal carina, posteroventral view; C) central part of fore wing; D) hind tarsal claws." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226078/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
). Discocubitus 
<emphasis id="B9332537FFC10838FB6DF9DF8598394D" box="[1173,1245,1622,1647]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">sinous</emphasis>
in its basal part. Ramellus and alar sclerites absent. Fore tibia spur without membranous flange (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FBD8F9F085CC39B1" box="[1056,1161,1657,1683]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1488,1512]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-16@29.[151,1436,181,1464]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 19. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) scutellum and propodeum, dorsal view; C) head, anterior view; D) head, lateral view; E) fore tibia spur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226076/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 19D</figureCitation>
). Claws very small with few short teeth (
<figureCitation id="137CE5A0FFC10838FEB5F91480F33995" box="[333,438,1693,1719]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1569,1593]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-231@30.[151,1436,669,1546]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Nyxia shawi gen. et sp. nov. holotype female (OÖLM). A) Mandibles anterior view; B) postpectal carina, posteroventral view; C) central part of fore wing; D) hind tarsal claws." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5226078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5226078/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="329">Fig. 20D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
